### Environment

- Angular: 15
- CDK/Material: 15.1.2
- Browser(s): Chrome 
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): Mac

### Feature Description

A breakpoint observer that observes the current component or component parent. Breakpoints on the component level allow you to create truly dynamic components.

For some time I've been using a library (that I created) called [angular-container-media-query](https://www.npmjs.com/package/angular-container-media-query) that does this in a suboptimal way. I was looking at ways to rework this and came to the conclusion that it would fit well within the `cdk/layout`.

The api for the `angular-container-media-query` library requires you to "register" a resize service:
```
import {MediaQuery, ObserveResizeService} from 'angular-container-media-query';

@Component({})
export class Component {
  @MediaQuery('(max-width: 400px)') @HostBinding('class.small') small = false;

  constructor(
    resize: ObserveResizeService,
    elementRef: ElementRef,
    changeDetector: ChangeDetectorRef
  ) {
    resize.register(this, elementRef, changeDetector);
  }
```

The api could more closely resemble the `BreakpointObserver`, but I'm not sure if that's possible:
```
import {ComponentBreakpointObserver} from '@angular/cdk/layout';

@Component({})
export class Component implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
  @HostBinding('class.small') small = false;

  small$ = this._componentBreakpointObserver.observe('(max-width: 400px)').pipe(
    map(({matches}) => matches)
  );

  constructor(
    private _componentBreakpointObserver: ComponentBreakpointObserver,
  ) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    this.small$.pipe(takeUntil(this.destroyed)).subscribe((small) => this.small = small);
  }

  ngOnDestroy() {
    this.destroyed.next();
    this.destroyed.complete();
  }
```

### Use Case

When you use for example a sidenav the content area resizes based on the sidenav being open or closed. A component within that content will better respond to size changes based on the content area size (or its own size) instead of listening to the breakpoints on the viewport.

I reused the dynamic sidenav example to show how the ContainerBreakpointObserver could work (and how it currently works with the `angular-container-media-query` library):
